'''''Aid on the Edge of Chaos''''' is a 2013 book on applying cutting-edge science and innovation to [[international development]], published by [[Oxford University Press]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199578023.do#.Uk7hGhbvyb8 |title=Aid on the Edge of Chaos: Hardback: Ben Ramalingam - Oxford University Press |publisher=Ukcatalogue.oup.com |date=2013-10-24 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> Written by global development and humanitarian expert Ben Ramalingam,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/ben-ramalingam |title=Ben Ramalingam &#124; Global development |publisher=The Guardian |date=2011-02-22 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> it focuses on the need to improve [[foreign aid]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/topics/international-aid-and-development |title=International aid and development - Topics |publisher=GOV.UK |date= |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> and the value of complex systems science and research for how global international aid efforts should be designed, implemented and evaluated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.santafe.edu/research/themes/human-behavior-institutions-and-social-systems/ |title=Complexity and social systems |date= |accessdate=2014-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106090804/http://santafe.edu/research/themes/human-behavior-institutions-and-social-systems/ |archive-date=2012-11-06 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

Described in a leading development journal as [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1467-7660 'one of the most lauded contributions to recent mainstream development thinking'], ''Aid on the Edge of Chaos'' has been endorsed by many top scientists and international leaders, including four Nobel Laureates in Medicine, Economics and Chemistry and the heads of [[Red Cross]] and [[United Nations]] as well as many NGO leaders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aidontheedge.info/quotes/ |title=Reviews &#124; Aid on the Edge of Chaos |publisher=Aidontheedge.info |date= |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> It has been positively reviewed by various press outlets, including ''[[The Economist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author =Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21601226-poor-and-benighted |title=The politics of foreign aid: Poor and benighted |publisher=The Economist |date=2014-04-26 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> the ''[[Financial Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author =Amy Kazmin |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/5e4ebccc-7312-11e3-b05b-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2yL7uAoC0 |title=Aid on the Edge of Chaos, by Ben Ramalingam |publisher=FT.com |date=2014-01-05 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author1=Heiner Janus |author2=Sebastian Paulo |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2013/dec/24/book-review-aid-edge-of-chaos |title=Aid on the edge of chaos - review &#124; Global Development Professionals Network &#124; Guardian Professional |publisher=Theguardian.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> ''[[New Scientist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22029471.100-look-to-complexity-theory-to-solve-the-aid-problem.html#.UrGnLxbEOlk |title=Look to complexity theory to solve the aid problem - health - 16 December 2013 |publisher=New Scientist |date=2013-12-16 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'',<ref>http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v503/n7475/full/503195a.html</ref> Lancet, Harvard Business Review and the British Medical Journal.

It was also the focus of an interview feature with the author in ''[[Huffington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dennis-whittle/ben-ramalingam-on-aid-and_b_805838.html |title=Dennis Whittle: Ben Ramalingam on Aid and Complexity |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=2011-01-07 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref>
''Aid on the Edge of Chaos'' was the subject of a public lecture by Ben Ramalingam at the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London, in December 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thersa.org/events/our-events/whats-next-for-foreign-aid |title=What's Next For Foreign Aid? |publisher=RSA |date=2013-12-05 |accessdate=2014-05-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203133836/http://www.thersa.org/events/our-events/whats-next-for-foreign-aid |archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref> an event chaired by [[Geoff Mulgan]], CEO of [[NESTA]]. The book was discussed by Ramalingam and Sir John Holmes at the [[Oxford Literary Festival]] in March 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oxfordliteraryfestival.org/literature-events/2014/Thursday-27/aid-on-the-edge-of-chaos-how-do-we-make-it-count |title=Ben Ramalingam and John Holmes Interviewed by Bidisha - Aid on the Edge of Chaos: How Do We Make it Count - 27 Mar 2014 |publisher=Oxford Literary Festival |date=2014-03-27 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> an event chaired by leading British filmmaker and author [[Bidisha]].

Many international aid agencies are applying ideas from the book in their work, including the UK [[Department for International Development]],<ref>{{cite web|author =Pete Vowles |url=https://dfid.blog.gov.uk/2013/10/21/adaptive-programming/ |title=Adaptive programming &#124; Department for International Development |publisher=Dfid.blog.gov.uk |date=2014-05-02 |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> United States Agency for International Development, the International Rescue Committee, Mercy Corps, UNICEF, World Food Programme, World Vision, the [[World Bank]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ieg.worldbankgroup.org/blog/simple-measure-complex-world#comments |title=Wanted: A Simple Measure of Success in a Complex World &#124; Independent Evaluation Group |publisher=Ieg.worldbankgroup.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref> the [[United Nations]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europeandcis.undp.org/blog/2014/02/06/innovation-for-development-scaling-up-or-evolving/ |title=Innovation for development: Scaling up or evolving? &#124; Voices from Eurasia - We help build better lives |publisher=Europeandcis.undp.org |date=2014-02-06 |accessdate=2014-05-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313042659/http://europeandcis.undp.org/blog/2014/02/06/innovation-for-development-scaling-up-or-evolving/ |archive-date=2014-03-13 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> and [[Oxfam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oxfamblogs.org/fp2p/the-aid-trilemma-are-complexity-scale-and-attribution-mutually-incompatible |title=From Poverty to Power » The Aid trilemma: are complexity, scale and measurability mutually incompatible? |publisher=Oxfamblogs.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-10}}</ref>

